hly revealing sources for understanding the culture, society, and politics of their periods. Though no English term even approximates it, “rhapsody” at least suggests the energy and recitative origins of the fu, which is a poetic form of tireless ambition that has been used for exhaustive descriptions of cities and palaces, as well as private reflections and lamentations, but also for carefully modulated political protest and esoteric ruminations on philosophical subtleties. In this volume, eleven essays by prominent scholars treat the fu from four major perspectives: its original use in court recitation; as a poetic genre with distinctive formal features; as a vehicle of philosophical inquiry; and as a major mode of political expression.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aChinese poetryxHistory and criticismvCongresses. 0aChinese poetryxHistory and criticism. 0aFuxHistory and criticismvCongresses. 0aFuxHistory and criticism. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Asian / Chinese.2bisacsh  aChinese poetry.  aimperial China.  alate imperial Chinese literature.  amedieval Chinese literature.  arhapsody.1 aCheng, Yu- yu, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJui-lung, Su, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLien, Y. Edmund, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMorrow Williams, Nicholas, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNeather, Robert, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSchoenberger, Casey, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aShih, Hsiang-Lin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aWilliams, Nicholas Morrow, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aZhangcan, Cheng, econtribut